  "doc_id": "46906",
  "text": "The relationship between clot mechanics and vascular diseases underscores the importance of identifying the contributory roles of platelets and fibrin to hemostasis. Several ex vivo mechanical tests of clot stiffness have successfully transitioned into the clinic, most notably the thromboelastogram (TEG) and rotational thromboelastometry (ROTEM). Measurement of bulk clot stiffness by either the TEG or ROTEM can be structured as a differential test to assess the relative contributions of platelets and plasma factors to overall clot stiffness [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
